quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
48,16,"Say to the bedouins who were left behind: “You will be called against those who possess great might and be asked to fight against them unless they surrender. {1} If you obey (the command to fight), Allah will bestow upon you a goodly reward. But if you turn away, as you turned away before, He shall inflict upon you a grievous chastisement.”",footnotes:1:The words au-yuslimuna in the original can have two meanings and both are implied: (1) That they should accept Islam. (2) That they should submit to the Islamic rule.
48,17,"There is no blame on the blind, nor on the lame, nor on the sick (if they do not go forth to fight). {1} Allah will admit those who obey Allah and His Messenger to the Gardens beneath which rivers flow and will inflict a grievous chastisement on those who turn away.",footnotes:1:That is
48,18,"Allah was much pleased with the believers when they swore fealty to you under the tree. {1} He knew what was in their hearts. So He bestowed inner peace upon them {2} and rewarded them with a victory near at hand",footnotes:1:About the tree under which this pledge was taken
48,19,"and with abundant spoils which they shall acquire. {1} Allah is Most Mighty, Most Wise.",footnotes:1:The reference is to the conquest of Khaiber and its rich spoils and this verse expressly points out that Allah had reserved this reward only for those people who had taken part in the Baiat Ridwan; apart from them no one else was entitled to take part in the victory and have a share in the spoils. That is why when the Prophet (peace be upon him) marched out to attack Khaiber in Safar
48,20,"Allah has promised you abundant spoils which you shall acquire. {1} He has instantly granted you this (victory) {2} and has restrained the hands of people from you {3} that it may be a Sign for the believers {4} and He may guide you to a Straight Way. {5}",footnotes:1:This refers to the other victories that the Muslim achieved successively after Khaiber.|181490:This implies the treaty of Hudaibiyah which has been described as a manifest victory in the beginning of the Surah.|181491:That is
48,21,"He also promises you other spoils which you have not yet taken, but Allah has encompassed them. {1} Allah has power over everything.",footnotes:1:Most probably this is a reference to the conquest of Makkah. The same is the opinion of Qatadah and Ibn Jarir. It seems to mean this: Though Makkah has not yet fallen to you
48,22,"Had the unbelievers fought against you at that time, they would have turned their backs (in flight), and would have found none to protect or help them. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
48,23,"Such is Allah's Way that has come down from the past. {1} Never shall you find any change in the Way of Allah.",footnotes:1:Here
